INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '402872fd-d7bd-4cde-a519-f40d2d048d0d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$tRPC vs REST — Verbs, Status Codes, and Idempotency Without the HTTP Ceremony$escape$,
  $escape$tRPC replaces HTTP's verb/resource model with a typed procedure graph. Your "resource naming" lives in router composition — `appRouter.user.profile` instead of `/users/{id}/profile`. Queries map to GET semantics: they're idempotent by convention, safe to retry, and tRPC's `httpBatchLink` sends them as actual GET requests when inputs are small enough. Mutations always POST — regardless of whether the operation is an update or delete.

tRPC doesn't expose raw HTTP status codes to clients. It surfaces `TRPCError` codes (`NOT_FOUND`, `UNAUTHORIZED`, `CONFLICT`, `BAD_REQUEST`) that the HTTP adapter translates to 404, 401, 409, 400. Throw the right code; the transport layer owns the status number.

Idempotency requires explicit design in mutations. Unlike REST where PUT carries an idempotency guarantee by spec, tRPC mutations have no such contract. Pass an `idempotencyKey` in your input schema, check for an existing record before writing, and return the cached result on replay. Your caller's inferred return type already matches — no extra plumbing needed.$escape$,
  $escape$import { z } from 'zod';
import { router, publicProcedure } from './trpc';
import { TRPCError } from '@trpc/server';

export const postRouter = router({
  byId: publicProcedure
    .input(z.object({ id: z.string() }))
    .query(async ({ input, ctx }) => {
      const post = await ctx.db.post.findUnique({ where: { id: input.id } });
      if (!post) throw new TRPCError({ code: 'NOT_FOUND' });
      return post;
    }),

  create: publicProcedure
    .input(z.object({ title: z.string(), idempotencyKey: z.string() }))
    .mutation(async ({ input, ctx }) => {
      const existing = await ctx.db.post.findUnique({
        where: { idempotencyKey: input.idempotencyKey },
      });
      if (existing) return existing;
      return ctx.db.post.create({ data: input });
    }),
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
